<br>
&quot;My liege, as you wish.&quot; Marlos Battleborne had only recently been inducted to the Vanguard of the Iron Crown, and still felt uneasy near such powerful creatures as this barbarian shamaness'. She wrapped her extra cloak close around her as she moved as close to the fire as the flames would allow. Her hair frizzling in wafts of heat even as her body convulsed with a new bout of shivers.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have a story... One of those creatures who some up here still doubt truly exist... A warrior even dears... It was huge, even larger than you my friends, with green skin and green blood and a stench that carries farther than believable and seems to never wash off. A Troll.&quot; Marlos smiled, as she knew this would hold even the mighty warrior's attentions. &quot;I was hunting in South Ro, past were the desert ends... There are orcs in that place too, though much less worthy foes than these... I was with out allies in those days and dodging the sight of the trolls and ogres the oft times roam those lands, but this one troll caught my eye. <br>
<br>
&quot;As I said, he is a warrior, and seemed my equal in standing though for certain far greater in power than I. He walked boldly into a camp of three of those green orcs. Now, as I saw it, they all seemed to be an easy battle even for me so long as there was only one, but this warrior walked into three. And the three orcs had at him. I feared for the warrior, and then for myself if the troll did run. I watched him closely as he battled. An orc fell to his blades, but he was far from healthy, as over half of his blood lay spilt across the green grass. <br>
<br>
&quot;The berserker fury took hold of him as he turned to his second orc. Having one orc on his back and one facing his blades the troll's blood spread across the battlefield. He was certain to drop in a blow or two when he turned to his final opponent. <br>
<br>
&quot;Oh did I wish at this moment that I had the gift of healing with the blessing of my Gawd, for he was a brave warrior and did not deserve this fate... I heard his bellowed and frenzied pray to Rallos Zek, and knowing we shared a common Gawd offered my prays for this troll warrior as well. &quot;Rallos Zek is not a meek gawd though. He demands that his minions be strong and makes them the strongest through trial. Our prayers were heard and answered when a passing orc did join his fellow in the final slaying of this troll... <br>
<br>
&quot;'RUN' I cried to him, knowing that no warrior with a heart of the Warlord would. His fate was sealed as he laid his blades upon the third orc from the camp and felt the wrath of the wondering orc as well. Any blow now meant his end. Ever blow he laid was a boasting right and a true gift from Rallos Zek himself. I watched this brave warrior's health closely. &quot;And the third orc fell... The troll turned his snarling face, covered head to toe in his own blood, and so near death that he was far from sane. His eyes did not see me, but only that orc still laying glancing blows upon his flesh. His bellowed war cry was one word, 'Zek'&quot; <br>
<br>
Marlos adjusted her cloak wishing she could climb into the fire as the cold still leached heat from her. She bent down to get some mulled brandy from the kettle she had propped on her spit. She needed the warmth inside her, and hopefully the brandy would ease her shakes. <br>
<br>
&quot;What happened!?!&quot; from the dark edge of the camp a grizzled veteran ranger shown eager eyes as he anxiously rubbed down his treant wood bow. <br>
<br>
Raising her eyes to the ranger, &quot;I'm sorry, what?&quot; Marlos appeared flustered and confused. She knew that she was thought of as frivolous and often laughed at as she froze, but now she had these on the edge of their seats and she was not going to let them off easily. &quot;Oh, yes. Umm, I was telling a story... Which was um..?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The troll! Orcs everywhere!&quot; Gargantua had seemed amused by Marlos' story, but was now nearly in tears as she held her laughter from her face. But the ranger did seem about to burst, as he gripped his bow stave and tried to retell the story by waving it about him. <br>
<br>
&quot;Oh!&quot; Marlos chirp, &quot;that one, yes of course.&quot; Marlos settled herself back down with her warm brandy and made eye contact with every member of their war party. &quot;The troll had survived the third orc of the camp, but if that wasn't unbelievable enough, he had that fourth orc having at him. He was in no condition to even stand, but he was insane with battle rage. He turned to the fourth orc and swung his blades at him. It was as though Rallos Zek had made him untouchable, but he was being touched. I watched that troll, and I could tell he was as dead as one can be and still have their breath in them. Rallos Zek had answered our prayers, but not like those weak gawds, but as in the fashion of a true Warlord among the gawds. He proved the value of his warriors and the power of his creed and the strength of the blessings he bestowed upon the warrior hearted... The troll warrior prevailed not from unlikely odds, but from impossible ones. <br>
<br>
&quot;I made my presence known to the warrior when he slew his final orc. As much as I dislike trolls and find no joy in their stench, I had a duty to do as a vassal of Rallos Zek. I offered my guardianship while he rested and tended his wounds. When he was of a fashion that could protect himself, I fled his presence to the trees. <br>
<br>
&quot;After all, duty is one thing, but a troll is still a troll.&quot; Marlos finished her story with her finger raised and every eye on her and every attention hers to direct. <br>
<br>
&quot;Bah!&quot; the old grizzled ranger stood quickly turning from the fire to seek a place a little less social mumbling in his wake about fanciful bard stories and foolishness in the elvish kind. <br>
<br>
But Marlos knew... Marlos knew the truth of her stories, and she knew the power her telling held. That ranger would never stand to challenge a troll warrior with out ample alliance to defeat it. And Marlos knew that in her telling, Rallos Zek had found praise and a bit more honor amongst the creatures of Norrath. <br>
<br>
As conversions and laughter found themselves dispersed by sleep, Marlos thought she heard a pray lifted from a warrior's lips to Zek... With a glad smile, she offered one of her own as sleep found her. <br>
 <p>Lady Marlos Battleborne
Bard of Rallos Zek
