<br>
Marlos Battleborne, a slight and seemingly frail elven bard, took heed of the Vanguard's call to arms. This is her story: <br>
<br>
I was whistling to the birds in South Karana when I received the call. Being new to the Vanguard, I wasn't sure I'd be wanted on such an important campaign, but I spoke my heart and was bid welcome. <br>
<br>
The Journey to Everfrost peaks was long, but I was not disheartened by it. I beat out a marching song on my drum and journeyed with all due haste to the homeland of the barbarians... Mind you this trip was not with out incidence, as in West Karana I happened upon a misshapen half wolf half human. It struck at me, and pursued me with ill intention, but I'd not be turned from my appointed course. A Knight of the Realm had ordained my mission and it had little to do with slaying those slow beasts called Werewolves. <br>
<br>
I met with Freja Honorsoul just outside of Halas where she told me of the horrors beset her people. Being bound by honor to Halas then, I made ready with the necessary supplies (an extra set of long under garments) and followed her lead to Redwind's lair. <br>
<br>
I had been to Everfrost peaks before, and had remember that the weather was chill there, but on the open plains with the wind's fleeting mercy, my poor elven joints did ache dearly. I remember thinking how could any race bare such a climate as that. I can not remember a moment of actual warmth the whole of the time I was in the Northern land... Though I did stop shivering a bit with the aid of some blessed honey mead. <br>
<br>
When we reached Redwind's lair I was to first meet the mighty barbarian Shamaness, Knight of the Realm, she whom I had pledged to follow upon this crusade, Gargantua Stormcaller... Now don't let her name throw you, she is huge in stature and in power, but only gargantuan in heart. <br>
<br>
We set upon the siege, and did well for Gargantua had with her allies to make the siege. Even as allies came and went, our siege of Redwind's estate went unhindered and with out casualty... I entertained, as is my way, with a story of other barbarian companions I have known. In turn, we received a story from a ranger of his mighty quests. <br>
<br>
And what should happen next? Wulfhere, an ally and friend for many songs happened upon our battleground. Being a barbarian Warrior with a handsome smile, Gargantua did not yield a moment in welcoming him to our war party... Perhaps she saw more than a warrior in that physique, but that'd be her business and not mine to say... Wulfhere, as is his way, had Cryton, his trusted shaman and closest friend, not far behind him... And so our war party was a frozen wood elf Squire, two Knights of the Vanguard, and allies, which included two of my most faithful friends. <br>
<br>
But as the siege raged on, Freja suffered illness upon her home front, and finally had to take her healing to her family's aid. We sought out more allies, and found them plentiful, but too often short in duration before more pressing matters did take them away... Gargantua Commanded, and the siege did not waiver. For days we did slay icy orcs, and many brave allies and even I a small and frozen squire found advancement in our chosen paths. <br>
<br>
But fatigue grew in Gargantua's eyes. The battle had raged and the siege never waived, but still the days were long and tiresome. She wisely made her way from the siege to seek rest among her home, bidding me, &quot;Hold the orcs at bay as long as you can, and Good Luck.&quot; <br>
<br>
Such had never been dreamed of and though often feared. I was but a squire, but the Vanguard's Siege upon Redwind lay solely upon my frozen shoulders and my trust in my allies. <br>
<br>
So there we were, a ragged band of what was once solid war party. Myself only a bard of my 25th song, with my poor elven heart forcing near frozen blood through my numb limbs. Wulfhere a mighty Wolf of the North using his 26th sharpening stone to keep his blade ever razor ready. Cryton our interpreter of Justice as all shaman of the north are, holding the 25th honor from his people. And a slight and frail druid who was short of wit and not long of tongue. <br>
<br>
We held. <br>
<br>
Redwind came upon us with fury, and we held. <br>
<br>
Our hap-hazard druid did find need to move on how ever prophesying our demise... Wulfhere, of great warrior wisdom, did say, &quot;We may not see day again... &quot; But there way no fear in his eyes, only fact. We were three, and we might not hold. It was truth, and it was the life of a warrior to know these truths. <br>
<br>
An Icy orc emerged, and we did not waiver for our siege.... We held... Another, and we held... Many others, and we held... <br>
<br>
Then it was Redwind whose fury did come to us in force. After many weeks of siege from the Vanguard of the Iron Crown, left with but a squire of the Vanguard, and two allies in support, he was enraged... <br>
<br>
For those of you whom never heard barbarian legend, Redwind is a shadow knight of great power. He has slain more barbarians than any other orc in recorded time, and is a name used to frighten children of the north under their covers at night... He is fierce. Redwind came upon us... <br>
<br>
We held... <br>
<br>
His icy orcs, whom are all oracles in nature, stormed us one after another, and we held... <br>
<br>
We held for days. Every battle a bare victory with our ragged band of three, but we held and did not forsake the siege... <br>
<br>
Not once did Cryton have even half of his magic in him.. <br>
<br>
…but we held. <br>
<br>
Not once did Wulfhere know complete health… <br>
<br>
…but we held. <br>
<br>
It was not Redwind that finally broke the Vanguard's Holy siege upon him, but sheer mental fatigue of my allies... I bid them to rest and to find peace in it, as each of us made our own private oaths to return one day and finish Redwind and his Dragonic Lord and Lady <br>
 <p>Lady Marlos Battleborne
Bard of Rallos Zek
