<br>
&quot;Yes dear, I am a part of the Vanguard. All be it, a small part. I am a Squire to the ninth circle and most recently I was in the service of Sir Yorie, Knight of the Realm.&quot; Marlos held the pride in her voice even as she sought only the sweat Honey Mead she had come for. <br>
<br>
&quot;A real knight! Truly a real knight!&quot; The youngster's eager presence was wearing on Marlos, but she had a soft spot for such enthusiasm. <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes dear, a real knight. He is in fact the Knight of the Realm amongst the Vanguard's ninth circle&quot; Marlos' eyes returned the depth of importance that title held. &quot;He was part of a siege on Mistmoore Castle, and I was there with him to serve.&quot; <br>
<br>
Marlos had found little pleasure in this service though. It wasn't anyone's fault but her own, for it was her lot in life. But needless to say she had ironed enough robes and polished enough wands to suit her for a long while. Yorie, being a wizard, was not taken to the great swords and shiny plate that some of Marlos' other liege lords. So while the great hero's of the Vanguard stormed the castle, she set up in the courtyard which to suit the vampyre's needs was truly a graveyard. <br>
<br>
&quot;Wow, you are the squire to a Knight of the Realm.&quot; A light glimmered in the young elf's eyes. &quot;And you've been to Mistmoore and lived to speak of it. What's it like? Did you see a vampyre?&quot; <br>
<br>
This elf was not going away as Marlos had hoped, but if it was a story he wanted, then that's what he'd get. &quot;So you want to hear of Mistmoore...&quot; a darkness fell over Marlos' voice. &quot;Get me a Honey Mead and I'll share with you a tale of woe.&quot; The drink was ordered and the tale began. <br>
<br>
&quot;The Vanguard set upon Mistmoore in force, calling forward their allied forces of the Sisters without Mercy and the Nomadic Brotherhood. It was the greatest fighting force I had ever witnessed. We had what we thought was the power to put an end to the Mayong's evil existence. We were brave, and we were powerful, and we were wrong.&quot; The young elf's face went white as he felt the horror of such a realization. &quot;We set up war parties and set to making our presence known to Mistmoore. We slew the familiars as we came upon them, but not with out our own loses. The most powerful of our forces did not find and slay these, as they sought access to the castle proper. So it was left to the young knights and squires to deal with them. Many squires died. I myself awakened more than once to the administering of a cleric for the Sisters Without Mercy.&quot; <br>
<br>
Marlos took a deep draught of her Honey Mead as she gathered her strength to face the memory, which she buried deep in alcohol. &quot;My Liege Yorie lead my fellow squires and I as far in as he dared. Squire Rizzo made a valiant effort to hold our flanks using his keen druidic senses to search out the dangers, which surrounded us. Squire Annzabeth cared for our wounded, which took nearly every moment of her time. I feared she would lapse under the constant flow of wounded, but she did better any other could have. And me?.. I spent most of my time scared of my own shadow and hoping the sun would never set.&quot; What could she say? She had done nothing but fear for her life, and the laundry while other did the important tasks. <br>
<br>
&quot;My Liege did release me from duty early, as I had not the strength of spirit to continue,&quot; That admission bought tears to Marlos' eyes. She was a bard of Rallos Zek and she had failed to hold her spirit. &quot;So I made my way back to the safety of Lesser Faydark under a musical mist. &quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Along the path I found an old friend, Squire Kylik. He was separated from his Liege, and desperate to get back. I saw him, but he did not see me, as my mist hid me from sight. I called out to him, and played my song with fervor to envelop him in it's mist. 'I shall get you there safely dear friend' I told him. Not willing to tell him why I was not with my own Liege. <br>
<br>
&quot;His liege was penetrating the castle walls, but I had given my word to get him there so I took him past the Ghoulish Ancille to the foyer of the concert hall. All was not well. The bodies of great knights, some I had known and some I had only heard of lay dead on the floor. My blood flowed like ice in my heart, but Kylik's liege was not among the dead. We checked the bodies all the while with the horrible gargoyle staring down at us and the teir'dal searching for signs of life that they might extinguish. I told Kylik to those things he's liege would bid him to bring and for us to make haste to the safety of Faydark. <br>
<br>
&quot;We made our way out back past the cemetery where my Liege had his post, but it was empty. They had been fallen upon and forced to flee. Kylik made move to arm himself for the defense of Vanguard's honor, as he is a warrior and that is their way, but in his haste, he revealed our position. 'Run' I commanded as I let the mist drop and chanted out a marching song. 'To Faydark or to Death' there wasn't time to be afraid. I pulled the Teir'dal to me and gave my fellow a count to distance himself. I was off on barely close enough to my friend to make his run a march and seeking the attention of any teir'dal along the way. <br>
<br>
&quot;Along the way I made note of a body. Many bodies lay within the boundaries of the Mayong's rule, but this one caught my eye. It was Annzabeth, my dear friend and an elf to whom I owe my life many times over. She did not deserve death, but there she lay as I ran by. <br>
<br>
&quot;Safe in Faydark we found Kylik's liege, and I bid him safety. I had to go back. Annzabeth was in there. I played a mist and went back past they very teir'dal that chased my to the edge of their master's land. To Annzabeth's side.&quot; Tears streamed down Marlos' face, but she couldn't notice. Her eyes were glazed with sorrow and Honey Mead and as the young elf looked on, he cried as well for her pain. &quot;Annzabeth, dear friend, I was not there to save you. She was dead, young one.&quot; Marlos' eye flooded her face as she looked upon the face of innocence. <br>
<br>
&quot;Rizzo came to collect her body. He said there was a cleric that may still be able to bring her back, but the pain in his eyes was too evident for me to believe there was not more than friendship in them. He was scared. For the first time in Mistmoore I saw him scared. Not for his own well being, but that he might have lost more than his life. He was scared that he mat have lost Annzabeth, and so was I.&quot; <br>
<br>
Marlos pushed her mead away from her. She'd had enough of that tonight. She had had enough of that. &quot;I went as deep into Mistmoore as I could trying to bring out the bodies of the dead. So many dead.&quot; Marlos drew herself up from the bar and held steady as she turned to the young elf, &quot;Your innocence is refreshing, but none that went to Mistmoore can ever be that way again. We have seen evil and once the knowledge that such exists in our world is a part of us, we can never be innocent again.&quot; Her word said, and a barroom filled with pained listeners, Marlos made her way across the street to the Traveler's Stay to room 4, her room. 1 copper a month, outrageous! <br>
<br>
&quot;Many entered Mistmoore, few returned unscathed&quot;<br>
