<br>
&quot;Go now to Guk and kill the Shin Lord.  He frequents a tavern in newer portion of that place.  If you do this great act and prove your bravery as well as loyalty to the Vanguard of the Iron Crown, I shall knight you myself, squire.&quot; Yppans Elemaster, Knight of the Council, Head of the Ninth circle of the Vanguard of the Iron Crown, Marlos Battleborne sworn Liege Lord had sent her here. <br>
<br>
The swamp stank, and Marlos was there alone...  &quot;Take any three Vanguardians you wish to accomplish this task, but they must not exceed you by more than 3 levels in their chosen professions, nor you exceed them by more than three.  I'll not be having another do this for you nor will I allow you to take one who would be slain for you in your escape.  Take heed Battleborne, I know whom your Gawd is, and be that as it is this task must be more stealth and tactic then frontal assault.&quot;  Yppans had been very clear that this was a task for a more tactic minded individual than he believed Marlos to be...  Marlos wondered if he was right. <br>
<br>
She had sought aid...  Kylik hefted his mighty axe and bid her good luck but misfortune had him need else where...  Annzabeth blessed Marlos and prayed to her own gawd for her well being, but the needs of the Norrath's sick and wounded had her time spent closer to great battles...   Rizzo found his family in greater need than a wood elf strayed from the forest and sought their company in nature...  Banes raised his war hammer in salute to Marlos' bravery, but found his life's calling demanded him to be closer to the dwarven hold...  So now Marlos Battleborne went forth to Guk, unaccompanied. <br>
<br>
Through the swamp she made her way.  Every on edge from the stench of trolls, but avoiding their sight.  Then on to the front entrance of guk. The Froglok Guards scowled at her, but did not leave their assigned posts holding cautiously against the trolls. <br>
<br>
Marlos had a song.  Digging in her pack she found her minotaur horn, a gift from an admirer ages past, and she played for the frogloks.  They we music lovers it seemed for the stop scowling at her though there were still dubious looks on their faces. <br>
<br>
The slime in Guk was everywhere.  Frogloks produces the on their skin, and it covered everything.  Marlos tried not to notice, but there were even places in the halls where she slid across the floor from the slippery slime. No matter how she tried, she was covered in it less time than it took to come across the first froglok. <br>
<br>
Marlos entered Guk, and played her music for those frogloks as well.  It seemed all frogloks like music.  On appreciative froglok sentry gave her warning that the Fungus people were not music lovers how ever and she best stand clear of that lot.  She asked direction to the tavern that she might have a drink and give a song or two.  She was on her way. <br>
<br>
She found the bar room, but the froglok would not server her.  From room to room she went, looking for a patron willing to trade drink for song, but none would even answer her hails to them.  Frogloks were very rude, but then this was not a pleasure trip. <br>
<br>
In the fourth room she found not Frogloks, but a human and two elves.  They jump as she entered and pulled her in.  With swords at her she was questioned, &quot;Who are thee!  State your allegiance!&quot;<br>
<br>
 &quot;I am Marlos Battleborne, Bard of Rallos Zek.&quot;  Marlos thought it best she keep her answers short and vague.  This was a place for her to make more known of her than she know of them.  &quot;and whom might you be sirs?&quot;  She was not about to let them think she was shaken by three armed males.  She was a bard of Rallos Zek and her boldness was not to be mistaken.<br>
<br>
 &quot;Rallos Zek!&quot; The rancor in the human's voice was clear. &quot;Don't tell me that war monger has thrown his lot in with these foul creatures.&quot;  It was clear by his arrogance that this human was no warrior, though his dress spoke other wise.<br>
<br>
 &quot;What are you doing here Paladin?&quot; Marlos made her prettiest expression.  If she had called him a shadow knight and he were a paladin, he'd kill her.  If he were a shadow knight, he'd find the mistake amusing, and then likely kill her for sport.<br>
<br>
 &quot;I am Kalvarin, Paladin of Erollisi Marr, at your service.&quot;  There was a lilt in his voice.  A paladin of the gawddess of love, no mistake had been made in recognizing Marlos' gender.  By Marlos' measure, he was a fool, as most paladins are and all men seemed to become when they thought her more woman than warrior. <br>
<br>
&quot;You have not answered the question Sir Kalvarin...  What are you three paladins doing so deep in Guk?..  Certainly you are not here for hospitality of the frogloks.&quot;  She gave a coy smile.  These might be the arms men she needed for her task. <br>
<br>
&quot;We are here to recover a holy sword.  A froglok lord has taken possession of it and as the sword is blessed but has no will of it's own, it serves him.&quot; His faces was expressionless, though it was clear it pained him to speak of such.  &quot;Lady bard, how much do you know of these frogloks you've come to entertain?&quot; <br>
<br>
Marlos did not correct him on his assessment of her purpose here.  For now that suited her until she learned more of these three.  &quot;I know little of anything.  I sing and play my music.  Little else matters, but please do share you story.  There may be a song in it.&quot;  Her lie did not weigh heavy on her as Rallos Zek had no displeasure from lies.  There was little honor in words truth or otherwise where the warlord was concerned.  You actions were what spoke your heart to him.<br>
<br>
 &quot;Ah yes.  Spoken like a true elvish bard.&quot;  A smirk covered the humans face as his fellows paid no heed to their conversation.  &quot;These frogloks have two gawds they worship.  Doing the biddings of each to further the biddings of the other.  They blasphemy both, and server both.  The foremost is Bertoxxulous, the plague bringer.  Every disease know can be found in this slime they have created by their very skin, just past this bar room you will find the fungus people being bred to serve Plague Bringer's needs.  Their second is a blasphemy in and of it's self, Rodcet Nife the Prime Healer.  So on one hand these creature spread disease in all of Norrath and on the other hand they fight disease plaguing the frogloks.  You will find among you audience froglok necromancers and even the Shin Lords whom call themselves paladins.&quot;  The human took a breath as Marlos made mental notes of his words and his demeanor.  &quot;We dear bard are not a strong enough band to root out the plague bringer's minions, so rather we are here to slay the blasphemers and reclaim the holy sword, Ghoulbane.&quot; <br>
<br>
Marlos was taken back.  She knew of Ghoulbane.  It was said to be the most powerful weapon of good on all of Norrath.  It's very presence banished evil undead.  &quot;I am not here to perform.&quot;  Her words were out before she had recovered her senses.  &quot;I am a squire to the Vanguard of the Iron Crown.  I am here to slay the Shin Lord as I was commanded by Yppans Elemaster, Knight of the Council.&quot; <br>
<br>
Silence...  &quot;Where is your war party Vanguardian?&quot;  Vattan, one of the high elf paladins, asked in disbelief. <br>
<br>
&quot;I have come alone.&quot;  Marlos was just starting to understand why this task must be done.  She had doubted that this was any more than just a test of her abilities, but now she knew it was not a test, but a task that needed doing.  A task she must do at all costs.<br>
<br>
 &quot;Alone!&quot; Vattan's voice rose, and found himself silenced by the hand of his fellow.  In elvish he continued, &quot;Go home girl.  this is no place for you. You are not a match for the Shin Lord, and you are a fool to do a rogue's duty young bard.&quot; <br>
<br>
Ignoring Vattan's uses of an unknown tongue, Kalvarin spoke, &quot;It is not the Vanguard's way to do such secretive one person strikes.  Why send you here alone?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I was not command to come here alone, it is simply how fate has made it... There are so many froglok's though.&quot;  Marlos wanted to cry as Vattan scolded her and Kalvarin pointed out the futility of her acts. <br>
<br>
In elvish, &quot;Go home child.  Leave this task to we whom must do it.  This is no place for a 29th song bard to find victory alone.&quot;  Vattan was not harsh in his words, for he himself was a 32nd level paladin, and found himself in harm's way as he warned her away from a young death. <br>
<br>
Kalvarin shrugged off Vattan strange ramblings, &quot;Marlos Battleborne, I have need of your service.  As a Vanguardian, I know I can trust this to you.&quot; His voice was even, but there was a light in his eyes.  He saw a victory in some secret war known only to him.  &quot;There is an envoy from Halas awaiting the arrival of the Shin Lord.  I believe they seek an alliance with the Froglok's.  If you can make it to them and make clear what the frogloks are about, perhaps you will have served Norrath more.  An alliance between barbarians and Frogloks would be unholy at best.&quot; <br>
<br>
Barbarian?  Marlos had spent a bit of time in that frozen land. and spoke thier tongue well.  What would those of the frozen north be doing here?  &quot;I shall look in on them, but I make no promises.&quot;  Marlos went to the door finding worry in the elven eyes that followed her and hope in those near blind human ones. <br>
<br>
In Froglok tongue, &quot;Barbarians may I enter to entertain you?&quot;  Marlos had mastered the Froglok's language, and coxed her voice to make even the most perfect gurgles and croaks that spoke her as a learned student of their tongue. <br>
<br>
&quot;By the Hammers of the Tribunal stop the racket!&quot;  A voice came from with in the room speaking common.  Something about it struck Marlos as familiar. She pushed by the curtain and entered the barbarian's room. <br>
<br>
In Barbarian tongue, &quot;Hail Barbarians.&quot;  Marlos looked upon the armored form seated in a much too small chair in obvious discomfort and as covered in slime as she her self had become.  &quot;Hail Wulfhere, Wolf of the North and slayer of Redwind.&quot; <br>
<br>
The barbarian shifted to look at her as he responded, &quot;I am Wulfhere, and Redwind did die by my hand, but to be honest that campaign was lead by a vanguardian Knight and our victory truly that of a simple squire... MARLOS!&quot;  As his eyes set upon the elven bard, his voice rang through the halls of Guk.  Upset croaks were raised in protest of his voice, but he paid them little heed.  &quot;Marlos Battleborne, is it truly you?  Zek curse my eyes if it isn't good to see you girl.&quot;<br>
<br>
 Before Marlos could respond the barbarian warrior had her under her arms and lifted to his face.  She had seen this act preformed with barbarian children all to often and felt her rising ire as she was treated as a child by this huge creature who was her friend.  She was seated on his lap as he called out, &quot;Shaman put away those magik potions and come in around here.  We've an honored guest.&quot; <br>
<br>
Cryton, Shaman of the Justice, came around from behind the warrior.  &quot;I heard, as I expect most of Guk heard brother.  Marlos.  It is good to see you again.&quot;  Cryton turned a scolding eye to his fellow.  &quot;Might be wise to let that lady down Wulfhere, mind you, she's not a child.&quot;  Wulfhere nearly dropped Marlos as he realized what he had done. <br>
<br>
&quot;I'm sorry my lady, I meant no disrespect...  It's just so good to see a friendly face.  We've been waiting here for weeks to...&quot; As Wulfhere told Marlos of Tribunal's judgment against the trolls and their sought alliance to destroy them,  Marlos shared what she had learned of the Frogloks. <br>
<br>
&quot;If such is as you say dear lady,&quot; Cryton's eyes narrowed as he sensed the wrong doings all around him, &quot;Then our tentative ally, is truly an enemy as well as those trolls whom surely trained Redwind.&quot;  Justice was in Cryton's blood.  He drank of it often.  Right and wrong, no gray was seen by him. <br>
<br>
&quot;I have come to slay the Shin Lord, Cryton.  I know now I can not do so alone and hope to survive, but it must be done.&quot;  Marlos had more here than Kalvarin had suspected.  She would not simply send the barbarians on their way.  She was Vanguard of the Iron Crown, and this was her battle field.  By Rallos Zek she would meet her enemy on it and by Zek she would be victorious.  &quot;Will you aid me in my cause dear Cryton?&quot; <br>
<br>
Wulfhere grunted.  Cryton may be the Shaman of Justice, but when had any shaman cut down an enemies arms men?  &quot;I will aid you girly.  Let the shaman think on it, but for me it is decided.&quot;  Wulfhere made his decision for himself no matter who he had set over himself.  &quot;As I followed you against Redwind, I shall follow you against the Shin Lord, and if necessary I shall cut you a path through an enemy army to get to him.&quot;  No boasting was in his words, and that made them set even harder in the air. <br>
<br>
&quot;My brother has spoken wisely, perhaps he should have been a shaman.  It shall be us three again then.&quot;  Cryton gathered his potions as Wulfhere belted on his twin blades. <br>
<br>
Marlos smiled to herself.  This time she had an army.  &quot;Not us three, dear Cryton.&quot;  Wouldn't those paladins be surprised.  &quot;Come and I shall show you&quot; <br>
<br>
Steel flashed as Marlos brought her barbarian war party into the paladin's chamber.  &quot;What is this!&quot;  Demanded Kalvarin.  His eyes wide as he looked upon the barbarian warrior.<br>
<br>
 &quot;A war party of Justice&quot; Marlos smiled as the 5 men introduced each other. <br>
<br>
&quot;Paladins come to kill a paladin?&quot; Wulfhere's words rang off sound even as he spoke them.  &quot;There seems no logic in that, but I shall like the aid if you are true, or cut through you if you are false.  I am here for the lady Marlos, and she believes in you.&quot; <br>
<br>
A smile fell over Vattan's face even as Wulfhere's words cut into Kalvarin's pride.  He knew the nature of barbarian's honor, and he knew that Marlos was all that truly mattered to the warrior in this party. <br>
<br>
Frogloks were lured into the room and slain systematically before they could call for aid.  Guk was used to the barbarians making noise and paid little heed to the sounds of sword play, as it was Wulfhere habit to practice often. <br>
<br>
After a long battle, the Shin Lord found his time to come to the bar room. Making his way to the barbarian's to discuss business he was shocked to find blades upon him, but not over whelmed.  &quot;What is this?&quot; he croaked out in Common tongue. <br>
<br>
&quot;We have come for the Ghoulbane,&quot; Kalvarin demanded as his sword was deflected by the Shin lord's lithe movements. <br>
<br>
&quot;Follow, I've not got the Ghoulbane.&quot; the Shin Lord dealt back blow for blow to his opponents.  &quot;Do you think me the only Shin Lord in Guk?  We are an entire guild, and it is one of my brothers whom has that great weapon.&quot; With a snarl the Shin Lord knocked a Kalvarin to his knees, but the fast magiks of Cryton's healings brought him back in force.  &quot;And you barbarians, coming under the guise of treaty!&quot;  The Shin Lord healed himself and had at Wulfhere with a vengeful ire.  &quot;I know now why we sent that orc to Everfrost to bring you Plague and suffering.&quot;  Glee was in the Froglok's eyes at those words.<br>
<br>
 &quot;Orc?&quot;  Wulfhere was off balance, and the Shin Lord took full advantage, putting a fatal wound in his chest.  &quot;Orc?&quot; as Wulfhere fell, Vattan caught him with a prayer and a single hand of faith.  Wulfhere lived. <br>
<br>
A scowl crossed the Shin Lord's face as Wulfhere regained his balance.  He ran out of the room ignoring Marlos' chains of music.  Hordes of Frogloks came to his aid, but Wulfhere was good to his word.  Cutting his way to the Shin Lord, &quot;What Orc!&quot; he demanded as the paladins widened the gap he cut. <br>
<br>
As the Shin Lord fell, he smiled.  He knew he had earned immortality in his life and that the Froglok Necromancers would bring him back even stronger as a Froglok Shin Ghoul Knight.  With his last breathe of life he whispered, &quot;May Redwind destroy you home and your children barbarian.&quot; <br>
<br>
Marlos acted quickly, grabbing the trophy of her victory, and calling for a full party retreat.  The paladins kept each other and the rest a live on their retreat, even as all the frogloks in Guk came down on them.  They made it out. <br>
<br>
Covered in slime and knowing the success of her mission, Marlos felt victorious.  As she turned, and looked into Kalvarin's face, that feeling faded.  &quot;A whole Guild of Shin Lords.&quot; his voice sounded empty.  &quot;We must go back.  The Ghoulbane must not be held by such as those.  If we must kill a thousand Shin Lords and a hundred thousand Frogloks, we must succeed.&quot; Marlos' heart sank. <br>
<br>
&quot;It's suicide.&quot;  Marlos knew her words were to be ignored, but she must speak them.  &quot;There are so many in that place that you will never make it back in, and if you do, then what?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Then we do what must be done, as is the way of a paladin.&quot;  Vattan's words were in Common for the first time.  Marlos wasn't sure he had known the tongue.  His fellow paladins nodding sagely as they worked to heal them selves and each other.  &quot;It may be a life's work, recovering the Ghoulbane. We may never find the Shin Lord who holds the icon of our faith, but we must follow that faith.&quot; <br>
<br>
Marlos was moved.  &quot;You paladins are fools, everyone of you.&quot;  There was no reply to her protests...  Wulfhere looked at her, and then to Cryton.... &quot;Well, don't just sit there, let's go then!&quot;  Marlos' stern look failed to hide her worry.  She'd not leave these brave fools in need. <br>
<br>
Wulfhere smiled and brought Cryton to his feet.  &quot;Right, back to battle.&quot; The barbarian warrior knew he was not expected to follow, and knew Cryton was expected even less.  But the barbarians were a race of honor and justice, and there was a debt to be paid. <br>
<br>
Raising a clouding song, Marlos brought her war party back their battle field with out incidence.  There they made their stand and slew frogloks and the occasional Shin Lord until fatigue of battle drove them home...   The Ghoulbane was not recovered, and the Paladins battle there still.<br>
