<br>
<br>
 Ahead of her in circle of trees she spied a familiar sight, though on she had not held since she fled her failure at the Guild of Faydark's Champions, the warriors guild where she learned of Rallos Zek and her own short comings in the skills of a warrior.  The in that circle was her father, which meant that her mother would be one of those trees. <br>
<br>
<br>
 She approached the old warrior working his sword.  Old is perhaps not the right word for his appearance.  He's an elf, and once an elf reaches 20 years, their appearance seldom changes.  This warrior Marlos sees as old, in fact retains all the youthful beauty and grace born in to every elf since the first had life breathed into her by the mother of all.  In Marlos' eyes, this warrior was as grizzled and battle worn as any human warrior would have been with a bare thousandth of his life's work. <br>
<br>
<br>
 &quot;I hear you approaching, elf.  Show yourself friend or foe.&quot;  With out breaking his attentions on his sword practice, the old warrior was alert to all of the world around him with startling detail.<br>
 &quot;Marlos!  You've returned to us...  Put your toys away you silly man and a make a welcome for you daughter.&quot;  To the unknowing eye, an ancient tree turned on it's roots and transformed into a female elf with such elegant beauty that none but another elf could behold her and not stare.  Her words came at a rush unheeding of the graceful tones that hung to them, but though the words were welcoming, the face of Marlos' mother was mixed worried concern and fearful expectation. <br>
<br>
<br>
 With out breaking his routine, the old warrior did not even spare a glance for his daughter returned from her long absence.  &quot;Come to steal my sword no doubt.&quot;  Shifting stances with a fluid movement which left no opening of an enemies blade, &quot;You call yourself a rogue now, no doubt.&quot;  Sword cutting the air first near his feet and not a breathe later at neck height for an ogre.  There was no doubt that this elf could put his wicked blade any where he needed it to go with out so much as a thought to what was needed.  &quot;I heard of your expulsion from the guild.  Couldn't even hold your tears to retain the last bit of your honor.  Well, under the circumstances, Scouts Guild was about the best you'd be getting.&quot;  With not even a glance to the women the warrior sheathed his sword with the grace and stature of a general before his armies.  &quot;That a child of mine should be a thief though, That I never considered.  You bring shame upon our entire clan.&quot;  With his words said, he started out of the circle with his back to Marlos and her mother. <br>
<br>
<br>
 Tears streamed down Marlos' cheeks.  She had spent her life wanting this one elf to be proud of her, and now he shunned her for reasons that held no truth.   She had never considered that she might become a dreadful rogue instead of a Bard.  What would she have done had she not had the musical aptitude that got her an invitation to the Song Weavers' Guild.<br>
 With desperation driving her, she sang with out a moments thought for words.  She had to hold her father from leaving.  She had to tell him she would never shame him.  She had to.. do something. <br>
<br>
<br>
 Stands of music wrapped around the warrior halting his departure, slowing his ever move.  With angry astonishment in his eyes he turned with extreme lack effort making his every move a labor of patience.  For the first time since her arrival, he looked at Marlos.  He just looked at her and made not another move. <br>
<br>
<br>
 Tears streaked her mother's face, &quot;Blessed Tunare!  She's a Bard!&quot;  Rushing to embrace her daughter, &quot;You are a Bard!  My heart's dearest, you are a bard.&quot;  Mother and daughter held each other as their tears fell on each other's shoulders.  Only another elf could have said there was a days difference in their ages, and that only with the manner they carried on.  To the eyes of the old warrior, there was no sight in the Faydark to draw his eyes from these two.  His Druid Bride with all the grace and beauty the she had when they married thousands of years before the birth of the most beloved elf in his life.  There they were.  His Bride and the Bard, not rogue, he had held while she took her first breath. <br>
<br>
<br>
 Even after the strands of music had faded, the warrior simply stood where he had been stopped.  When the women approached him, one timidly and the other with a reproachful look in her eyes which promised an eternity of paying for his rudeness, he stood his ground.<br>
 &quot;Father, I am sorry.  Please forgive me.  I wasn't thinking and I acted hastily.&quot;  Tears rang in Marlos' voice.  She knew that she should not have bound him, but she was ready for whatever her punishment would be. <br>
<br>
<br>
 &quot;Daughter, my Dearest Marlos, I know better than to taunt and then turn my back.  I'm just lucky you didn't put a knife in me.&quot;  For the first time in too long, Marlos felt the smile of her father beaming at her.  She knew why she had come home.  &quot;Tell us of your adventures and how you managed to get into the most exclusive Guild in the Faydark.&quot;<br>
 Marlos told her story, and smiles to to looks of Astonishment. <br>
<br>
  <br>
<br>
 &quot;Vanguard of the Iron Crown!&quot;  Her father's voice still crackled with emotion when he repeated words.  &quot;Knight Lieutenant and Knight Diplomat!&quot; <br>
<br>
 &quot;Oh hush dear.&quot;  With a druids calm, her mother had absorbed every word of her child's adventures.  &quot;So tell me about this High Elf Paladin you find so worthy of you attention.&quot;<br>
 With a blush, Marlos continued on with her most recent battles.  &quot;There is an out post of trolls in the Mountains of Rathe.  I have caught a taste for killing trolls, but with the rediscovery of the Kunark continent.  I think I must head there.  I fear the Vanguard may need me at this already.&quot; <br>
<br>
<br>
 &quot;Trolls!  You kill trolls!?&quot;  Marlos had never seen her father so agitated, and she did not know how to take his reactions to her stories.  She wasn't lying to them, and she was perfectly honest about how scared she was most of the time.  Her father just didn't seem to grasp her stories. <br>
<br>
 <br>
 &quot;If your Comrades in Arms are waiting for you, then I guess you must go soon.&quot;  Her mother seemed all to willing to accept anything and everything she told her and fish out only which of the men she had thought were brave and valiant.  &quot;After all, with out you keeping an eye on him, it sounds like that Mapleleaf boy will go off and get himself killed.&quot; <br>
<br>
<br>
 Marlos made ready to go as her mother and father spoke quietly amongst the trees.  As she got her bearings and prepared to head to the dwarf docks, her father came to her side.  <br>
<br>
 &quot;Marlos,&quot;  She turned to him ready to defend her stories and argue her case against what ever her father had decided she was lying about.  &quot;my Dear one, I am honored to have you as a daughter.  Come back to us alive once more when your duty is served.  We love you and we are proud of you.&quot;  With that, Marlos saw what no warrior had ever seen, and she had never dreamed was possible.  She saw a tear in her father's eye.  She kissed his cheek and began her long run back to the Vanguard of the Iron Crown.<br>
