<br>
&quot;Marlos, dear Tunare it is you!&quot; Wunderr Mapleleaf greeted her with open arms. &quot;I feared you might never come back to us. You have been gone a long time.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I said I would return, and I have...&quot; Marlos' eyes darted across the faces of the Vanguard, marking the new ones for memory and searching out her old faithful companions. &quot;Wunderr, Dear you have a battle hardened look to you. When I left your side you I had never considered you so formidable. What have you seen of this continent to make you such?&quot;<br>
<br>
Wunderr's eyes darkened with memories of war and death. &quot;It is a dangerous place m'lady. But the Vanguard has met the danger and flourished.&quot; A smile move across Wunderr's lips never touching the darkness in his eyes. &quot;Let me introduce you to those you do not yet know, and present you to the Vanguard as returned to us.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
The Vanguard sweep of the Frontier Mountains went well, but Marlos felt the loss of family she did not see among the Vanguard. War and shaken morale had taken it's toll on her family, but the Vanguard's numbers were bolstered by the introduction of valiant heroes to carry them forward into the breach. It is these new heroes Marlos focuses on as she sang her songs to her family and raise spirits where she could.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you for coming&quot; A Ranger told her. &quot;It is nice to finally meet the Lady Marlos in person.&quot; His face bore battle scars, and more lines of deep thought. Not so handsome as an elf, but far more that a human. His eyes held a light that seemed to shine through Marlos.<br>
<br>
&quot;I wouldn't have missed it m'Lord.&quot; Marlos' felt uncomfortable before this Ranger's eyes, which bothered her to her core. She had stared down Trolls and made them flee in terror, or stood toes to toe with a giant never fearing for her and her fellow's victory. This ranger had no right to look at her such. How dare he!<br>
<br>
&quot;IF you ever need me, m'Lady- call and I will be to your side.&quot; There was no lilt in the Ranger's voice to imply more than the comradery of his words. With no ceremony, he was gone.<br>
<br>
Marlos fumed. &quot;At least he could have...&quot; Startled, Marlos put an end to that thought before she had to admit to herself what she'd have wanted him to do. <br>
&quot;What has he done to me?&quot; Marlos pondered the thought as she went out to explore the land of Kunark.<br>
<br>
----<br>
<br>
<br>
Called out to the Guild, &quot;Who is coming to Trakanon's Teeth to help get keys to Old Sebilis?&quot; The Ranger's words echoed in Marlos' mind. She was going to to hunt Bloodgill Goblins to recover a coin for Wellin Fargan. She did not have time to waste looking for keys to a forgotten city's ruins.<br>
<br>
&quot;I was going to hunt Bloodgills, but you can count me in.&quot; Marlos' words went out to the Vanguard even before she had decided what she was about. She did not want to hunt frogloks forager and hunters, why did she commit. They didn't need her, and she is far from needing a key. &quot;I wouldn't miss it for the world.&quot;<br>
<br>
She met the Ranger again in the Swamp of No Hope. She had see him about Norath at Vanguard gatherings, but she had avoided his eyes. This time there was no avoiding his gaze as the stood face to face. He had taken the form of a wolf, but his eyes were the same.<br>
<br>
Marlos wondered if she was taking an ailment. Her heart raced, and she sweated as she felt a chill. &quot;I really wanted to go hunt Blood Gill Goblins today, but since you are gathering Vanguard here, I will never be able to get enough together to do what I wanted to do.&quot; She turned an accusing glare on the wolf.<br>
<br>
&quot;I will help you afterward if you like m'Lady.&quot; The Ranger's voice seemed to douse Marlos' anger with it's first sounding, and by the time he had made his promise all Marlos could do was grumble half heartedly.<br>
<br>
Vanguard formed up and defeated those that came against them. Marlos held herself away from the Ranger, and he seemed oblivious to her as he thought only of seeking out frogloks and luring them back to their deaths in the trap set by the Vanguard. <br>
<br>
&quot;You sing beautifully m'Lady.&quot; Marlos jumped at the ranger's voice off to her side. What was HE doing sneaking up on her like that?! The nerve of some men!<br>
<br>
&quot;It's my job, dear.&quot; Marlos replied curtly to forestall any conversation the Ranger might have hoped to make by his sneaking tactics.<br>
<br>
&quot;We have gotten Keys for everyone, now where does everyone want to go?&quot; The question posed to the party was Marlos' que. She needed to be away from this Ranger's continual presence, and the palpable loss of it when he ran off scouting.<br>
<br>
&quot;I need to get the coins for the banker. I said I would, and I need to.&quot; Marlos put that thought in her mind, and fled from all other thoughts that crept in on her.<br>
<br>
&quot;There is one held in Kaesora, so we go there. Who is with us?&quot; The Ranger's voice seemed to mock Marlos' hopeless desire to ignore it as it rang true in her mind.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll go.&quot; Korez, Tanilla and Chevalier spoke up immediately. Soon followed by the agreement of others. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
As the journey side tracked some party members, they found themselves numbering 4 at the Field of Bone. To Marlos' joy and turmoil, the Ranger was there still. Infact, there were 3 rangers, a rogue and her. Not a great healer amongst them, but only the one ranger seemed to have her in a distraction.<br>
<br>
They moved into the crumbling ruins, and jumped blindly into the depths of the forgotten hells. Spiders were on them as they made their way, ever jumping from skeletons and ghosts. Nothing posed a great threat to their combined skills and the rangers made haste at practicing their meek healing abilities.<br>
<br>
The Ranger would go out looking for monstrous beasts to bring to the small group to destroy, and each time Marlos' heart wept for his absence. Why did he have to go?! What's he trying to prove? Crazy foolish Ranger!<br>
<br>
Time wore down and soon the Rogue had to take leave of thier presence. There was no fear in her, as Chevalier left for more pressing matters.<br>
<br>
As Tanilla slept, Korez, and Marlos waited for the Ranger to return. The three of them battled on, but the lack was felt and they were soon not having the ranger venture far beyond the immediate area. <br>
<br>
Tanilla returned to us, and our strength of arms with her, but Marlos feared for the ranger's safety as he ventured out. <br>
<br>
As they battled on, a second monster fell upon them, and then a third and a fourth came into being as they wagered their lives on victory.<br>
<br>
Korez fell, to the 5th beast that came upon his blind side with a crippling assult. His loss was not long followed by Tanilla as the murdering mob turned it's attentions to her. Marlos called to two of them, and knew they would not last if Tanilla fell.<br>
<br>
Marlos and the Ranger stood side by side, as in some warrior's dream, facing down the monsters with no hope of retreat or salvation. Marlos watched the ranger out of the corner of her eye. His face a study of warrior calm. The same warrior calm that held Marlos' knees from shaking. Why doesn't he call a retreat, at least to the spider covered rooms so that we might have hope that some one might find us before we decay and become a part of the undead citizens.<br>
<br>
There was no retreat. No warrior would have called one, except to save his fellows. Here death was coming, and this Ranger held with a warrior's heart. Marlos' fell, and her last sight was of the Ranger guarding her body with his sword and life against impossible odds.<br>
<br>
-----------<br>
<br>
<br>
When Marlos opened her eyes, she could not even remember her name, but the vision of a Ranger standing over her as a guardian angel was hard in her mind. &quot;You are resurrected lady elf. Sit and take the time you need to clear the clouds from your mind and return life and strength to your limbs.&quot; A cleric was there. Marlos thought he must be a cleric anyhow, but what she was, she did not know.<br>
<br>
&quot;There was a Ranger.&quot; The voice sounded famuliar, and it came from her throat. There was a Ranger, of that she was sure.<br>
<br>
&quot;They are well. They are resurrected and their minds and bodies are well. They wait outside.&quot; The cleric's voice was comforting.<br>
<br>
&quot;They?&quot; Marlos' mind swarmed with things she knew she knew. &quot;There was a Ranger. He was here, and he was...&quot; Her words trailed off as he mind swooned with confused thoughts. She stumbled outside and was accosted by the roar of living voices.<br>
<br>
&quot;Marlos!!!&quot;, that's what her name was! Fattik ran up and hugged her. She knew him, and she knew the cleric with him, Annzabeth. &quot;We came as soon as you came up missing.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;With an army?&quot; Marlos' eyes fell on Joaquin, and Aliena, and Vanguardians, and Nomadic Brothers, but where was the ranger? &quot;I must find someone Fattik, please excuse me.&quot;<br>
<br>
Marlos found Korez and Tanilla. She had her wits back, and she remembered their plight. &quot;Where...&quot; The Ranger returned from scouting up the hall cutting Marlos' words short as she release a breath she did not know she had held.<br>
<br>
&quot;Marlos! Good, I was getting concerned.&quot; The Ranger seemed to pass over her with his eyes and then ignored her. Marlos wanted to cry.<br>
<br>
&quot;Joaquin, dear can you take us out of here.&quot; Marlos called her dear brother close. &quot;I need to go to Ferroott.&quot;<br>
<br>
Joaquin knew his sister well. He did not ask any questions, since she had not abandoned to the world when he proclaimed his love for a dark elven ShadowKnight to their parents. &quot;To Ferroott we go.&quot;<br>
<br>
-------<br>
<br>
In Ferroott the group said their farewells, and Joaquin whispered to Marlos the words of a brother. &quot;He's cute for a halfhuman, but if you keep staring like that you might actually see him aging.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I need to go see Zulort, Joaquin. I am not well, and I need prayer.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You are well, Marlos.&quot; Joaquin grinned evilly, &quot;but you do need prayer.&quot; Marlos ran off to try to seek the answers for her troubled heart, as Joaquin mused to himself over his baby sister's elven adolescence. <br>
