Most days she would be comforted by the surrounding trees of the Ferroott, but she hardly noticed them today. Troubled by recent events and the ever present strain on her heart that pulled her to Kunark. The Ranger was there, somewhere- but Marlos refused to admit that it was a pull to him -It was Kunark she found alluring, not the presence of a Half-human.<br>
<br>
As she made her smiles in passing to the Oggok Guards, cursing Cazic Thule under her breathe for his taint on the Ogres of Oggok, her thoughts wandered to to what she would say to Zulort.<br>
Marlos respected the Ogres. Like the Giants and orcs, Ogres were the creation of the Warlord, made solely for the purpose of battle.<br>
Zulort, High Shaman of the Shaman of War, was waiting in the guild house in his normal spot as Marlos approach.<br>
&quot;Ullo lil'alfie. Hu yu ta dey?&quot; Marlos smiled dispite her mood. She knew that slanted words disguised a wisdom that ran deep in this Ogre.<br>
&quot;Honestly, Great Zulort, my heart is heavy.&quot; With a light voice she shared with Zulort all that weighed on her soul, and though she tried not to be forth-right about the Ranger, she could not hold the truth from The sly ears of the High Shaman.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hur Hur,&quot; Zulort's booming laughter echoed off the walls. &quot;Wut yu tink yu hab wrung wit yu, Merlus?&quot;<br>
<br>
Marlos had hoped and even convinced herself that Zulort would simply have a magic enchantment that would lift her heart. Why was he asking her what this ailment was. After all he was the shaman! &quot;I don't know! I think it must be a curse, or a charm spell. Maybe Agalkin is playing a joke on me.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Dis no mojo dat be werked. Dis be da werks ub eh mich mer powrfil ting...&quot; Taking a momment to look at Marlos as he arranged his thoughts, Zulort began to smile. &quot;Hu ole er yu, Merlus? Ib yu wer un Ogre, whut be yu?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;How old am I?&quot; Marlos had seen human cringew from the truth of that question, but Zulort was not really asking her years so much as her youth. &quot;I am 340 years old. For an elf, that's about the same as a 90 year-old Ogre, or even a 16 year old human.&quot; Marlos had never really thought about what her age might mean to others. She had been accustom to her immortality before her mother would even let her leave the high trees of her home.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yu be bery ole Merlus, bit yu be bery yung tu. No be ole nuf ta merri ib yu be an Ogre, bit yu no a Ogre.&quot; Scratching his head Zulort studied the Lady elf he had grown to respect. Trying to see her as a young Ogre, while looking at her tiny elf form. The years she had seen would make her a middle aged Ogre if she had been born of his own race, and that made the reality even harder to understand. &quot;Merlus, um... Yu kno were babs cum ferm?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What?! What kind of question is that? Of course I know where babies come from.&quot; Shock rang the respectful tone from Marlos' voice. &quot;I am not doing that either. I am not even old enough to think about that! What kind of sick thing are you suggesting?! I am not...&quot;<br>
<br>
Waving his large hands to fend off the onslaught of Marlos' words, Zulort recoiled from the little elf's flying hands. &quot;Me jus askin! Me no use ta takin ta alf girs bot dis duf!&quot; As Marlos seemed taking her second breathe to continue her verbal assult, Zulort found himself the only redirection he could to a girl of this age. &quot;Meyhap yu sud tak ta yer mudder bout dis. Me no gud wit girs firs lub pans.&quot;<br>
<br>
Caught off guard Marlos could only repeat the words that Zulort had thrown out in haste. &quot;First Love Pains...&quot; she whispered. &quot;but I am too young for...&quot; Her words trailed off as her heart strangled the denial from her thoughts.<br>
Tears refused thier captures any longer as they ran down Marlos' cheeks. Zulort's heart broke as he watched Marlos stand there crying. &quot;Eben da grat Warlord, Rallos Zek, ken't tel da Merr ladi ta no tuch er herts. Yu a gir, Merlus. Ladi Merr wil tuch yu. Dat wut she du.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But he's a half Human!&quot; failing to put her normal contempt in the racail title. &quot;Humans live so briefly, and the mixed blood only lengthens thier pain.&quot; Marlos' tears flowed with no thought as she strained through the horror of her hearts desires. &quot;I can't love a human, Zulort. Even a half human.&quot; Zulort took her in his hands gentlely holding her like a small Ogre child. &quot;Even a being half elf, he could live much more than 500 years, and then I have to watch him die... I can't do it!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Dat yer chos. yu ken lub em fer 500 yers, and den lus em, er yu ken lus him now en no hab yer 500 yers wit em.&quot; Gentlely petting the little elf's back, Zulort spoke a softly and tenderly as an Ogre's voice allows. &quot;eder wey, yu lus em, me lil alfie. Yu jus hab to chos wen yu du.&quot; <br>
<br>
As Marlos lay in Zulort's hands, holding tight to his massive fingers as she cried, Zulort hummed an Ogre Lulaby often heard in the nurseries of Oggok.<br>
<br>
------- Later on the Continent of Kunark<br>
<br>
Lady Marlos Battleborne walked through the enterance to the Castle of Karnors. With a determined step she ducked arround the inhabitants who searched for the invaders of thier lair.<br>
<br>
She had tracked the Ranger to this castle. The Vanguard knew that he was leading a raiding party against the hordes the plagued the Dreadlands. Marlos would join that raiding party, even if she had to make her way deep into this dangerous lair to do so.<br>
<br>
She found the Ranger's band of brave souls inside the walls, camped by the Moat. &quot;Hail&quot; Marlos called to thier sentries to alert them to her presence in a way that would not decorate her with fletching.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hail Marlos&quot; Called a voice in return. &quot;What bring you alone to such a place Lady Bard?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I seek to join your party. If you have a place for a lonely bard.&quot; Marlos would not take no for an answer no matter the sittuation.<br>
<br>
&quot;Welcome Marlos&quot; the Ranger's voice made her jump in her skin. He was there. She had found him, and now she just had to make him find her. <br>
<br>
&quot;Hail&quot; Marlos offered to theparty and settled into the corner barely glancing at the Ranger as she walked past him. <br>
<br>
The Ranger looked at her as she found a place by the fire and started to chat with one of the casters. His eyes lingering on her for only a momment before the alarm was given that a Drovlarg was come close and needed to be done away with.<br>
<br>
------ Later as the battles lulled<br>
<br>
&quot;Hail Lady Marlos&quot; the Ranger settled next to the fire where Marlos was tuning her Mandolin. &quot;Did the banker like the coin collection?&quot;<br>
<br>
Looking at the Ranger, Marlos strained to make out his words as her mind swirled. &quot;Yes.&quot; She should say more, but what? She needed to say more, the silence was lingering. What can she say? Panic was edging in...<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh...&quot; The Ranger broke the silence. &quot;That's Good.&quot; He eyes turned away from Marlos' studied work on her instrument. &quot;Well I need to... Well, you know, we all have our work.&quot; With that the Ranger was gone to speak with another as Marlos plucked at the strings on her mandolin testing thier tones.<br>
<br>
Putting down her mandolin Marlos stared off into the fire. What was she doing here. She couldn't even string two words together with this Ranger looking at her. She had over tightened on of the strings on her Mandolin and almost ruined it as the silence had dragged on between them. 'Oh that would have been great' Marlos admonished herself, 'snap a string in front of him and make a fool of yourself- that'll impress him!'<br>
<br>
------ Time passed slowly<br>
<br>
Marlos refused to follow the Ranger arround, but she always found herself going where ever she could find him. Very Few words passed between them, and she was losing hope.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aliena, I just can't get him to notice me.&quot; Marlos sat at the druid circle in the Dreadlands talking with he fellow Vanguard, and dear friend.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, maybe he's just the silent type, or maybe he thinks you are just kidding when you flirt with him.&quot; Lady Aliena Heartbreaker had joined Marlos for a bit of Rabbit Stew, and tea. She had not known that her young friend had started noticing the males of Norrath, but found it very entertaining to try to advise Marlos on one of her favorite pass times. &quot;I know when I flirt with him, he just laughes me off becuase he knows I am just kidding.&quot;<br>
<br>
Marlos' skin heated with a fury that had no place in her heart. What was Aliena doing flirting with her Ranger! &quot;But I don't know how to flirt. I mean I am really no good at it, and don't even know where to start.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;We all flirt Marlos!&quot; Aliena Laughed at her dear friend. &quot;You just don't realize you do it, and maybe that's your problem.&quot; Aliena considered Marlos with a raised eye brow. &quot;I don't know what to tell you, except that if he really means something to you, don't give up.&quot;<br>
<br>
Marlos sighed, clearly disappointed. She had hoped Aliena would know some secret for making a male notice her. Apparently, there wasno secrets, or if there were, Aliena wasn't sharing. <br>
Marlos squinted at Aliena trying to make out if she was hiding something... 'This is dumb.' Marlos admitted to herself. &quot;Do you think I should be more forward, I mean what if he takes it the wrong way. I want him to notice me, but I don't want him to think I am offering something I am not.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Just be yourself Marlos.&quot; Darue spoke up from the side. Marlos had all but forgotten him as she and Aliena spoke of her failed attempts to capture the attentions of her Ranger.<br>
<br>
&quot;Men&quot;, Marlos grunted to herself. If they how dare they do what they do and then expect her to pertend that everything was normal. &quot;It's not that easy, Darue.&quot; Marlos said dismissing the interruption.<br>
<br>
&quot;Actually Marlos, some times that works. Be forward, but be yourself. Maybe you might want to try being honest with him.&quot; Aliena voiced in support of Darue's offered advice, then added in a whisper, &quot;I would never try the honesty thing with men, but hey! it could work.&quot; Laughing Aliena turned her attentions back to Darue leaving Marlos to drown in her own confused dispair.  <p>Lady Marlos Battleborne
