Marlos didn't look up, making her way quickly to her chambers.  She couldn't bare to look upon her friend's faces, not now- never again.<br>
<br>
&quot;Vanguardians!, gather to me!&quot; the summons rang through the hall, and Marlos knew she had to go, or all would be insulted by her absence.<br>
How could she go?  After the unholy bargain she made to save her own life.  She had to leave- She had to flee her own failures.  She couldn't stay any longer.<br>
<br>
&quot;Marlos?&quot;  Malceor's voice called into her chambers.  Blessed Malceor with his boyish innocence, tear streamed down Marlos' face.  &quot;Come on you silly elf, the council has been called, we must go.&quot;<br>
&quot;It's over, my dear ranger.  It's all over.&quot;  Marlos' voice trembled as she spoke, her bardic range failing her in shrilling sobs.<br>
&quot;What's happened?  Marlos! What's over?&quot; panic seeped into Malceor's voice as he watched Marlos break down.  &quot;Tell me dear bard, please tell me.&quot;<br>
<br>
Marlos Told:<br>
<br>
The city of Neriak holds awe and horrible wonders for any bard, but for a wood elf, to see the results of Innoruuk's Hatred was an alluring horror indeed. <br>
Marlos wandered the alleys of the dark city once more drawing resolve from the horrors her eyes touched.  Elves should never be what these have been made.<br>
<br>
&quot;You are known as Marlos!&quot;  a voice came out of the darkness behind her, and as she turned toaddress it, &quot;You will come with us!&quot;  The Dragoons were upon her, but with no weapons bared, she would not try to flee.  But then, she could not have fled if she had tried, with the bad Resonance in the underground city.<br>
<br>
Passing through the Neriak Commons, the Dragoons lead Marlos deep into Neriaks 3rd Gate past the Temple of Innoruuk to the Library.<br>
<br>
As they entered the room, a scribe of Innoruuk looked up from his ledger.  Hardly an intimadating elf, this scribe held all the authority over the city's commerce and the payroll for the guards.<br>
&quot;Ah, Marlos.  I am so glad you could join me today.&quot; a wicked smile held frozen on the scribe's face.<br>
<br>
&quot;I had not any choice, and you had no right to have be brought.&quot;  Marlos return sadistic smile for sadistic smile with this elf.  She was a dark elf, she had to play the dark elf.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have all the right I need.  You are known as Marlos, and I know that name.  Marlos Battleborne of the Vanguard of the Iron Crown.&quot;  His smile never wavered as Marlos' heart froze in her chest.  &quot;I see you know that name as well, dear Lady.&quot;<br>
<br>
Screams rang through Neriak, but that was not uncommon.  What day in the centuries did Neriak ever know a time with no screams.<br>
Torturing the wood elf, the scribe showed no more care than he had over his ledgers, and no less skill.  Days crawled by, centuries by Marlos' measure of pain, but truly only days.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am satisfied with your songs bardess.&quot;  there was no sacrasm in the scribes eyes, but then the Teir'dal would call screams music.  &quot;and you do not prove worth killing.&quot;<br>
<br>
A shattered form of an elf cowered in the corner of the chambers.  She had a name once, if she could just think of it.  She was not insane yet, she would not be insane yet, she would not be insane yet.  She could feel the spiders crawling over her, and the scorpions stinging her.  &quot;They aren't real&quot;  she mumbled to herself.  The couldn't be real, or she would be able to get tem off.  They couldn't be real...<br>
<br>
&quot;It seems that Neriak has never had a bard who was welcomed openly, and since I don't believe you are a threat to this great city, I will grant you leave.&quot;  the scribe dipped his feather quill into the ink jar and penned a writ upon which he deftly scribed the word &quot;Marlos&quot;<br>
<br>
That's it, the heap of flesh quivered as she began to laugh.  &quot;Marlos!!&quot;  She called her name through the shatters ruins of her face.  &quot;I am Marlos Battleborne, Bard to the Warlord&quot; He had given her name back, this kind elf with the dark skin.  She had her name back.<br>
<br>
Smiling that unwavering smile at the ruined elf, the scribe answered in softly caressing tones, &quot;Yes you are.  You are Neriak's First Bard.  However, some will not welcome you so be sure not to go where you are not welcome.&quot;<br>
<br>
The spiders were gone, and the stings faded.  &quot;I am Marlos Battleborne, Neriak's First Bard.&quot;  The ragged wretch trembled as she repeated the scribe's words unhindered by doubt.<br>
<br>
&quot;You are welcome her as you are, dear Marlos.  No need for guises any longer.  You are the sole wood elf in Norrath welcomed here by the Guards.&quot;  Turning from the heap in the corner that had once been a Vanguard of the Iron Crown, &quot;Take her to Forest and leave her.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Tears streamed down Marlos' face as she told the story, the details still buring her mind.  &quot;It's over.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes.&quot;  Malceor comforted his beloved bard.  &quot;You are back with us now.&quot;  Marlos moved away from him as though he were an danger to her.<br>
<br>
&quot;NO, it's over.  It's all over.&quot;  Marlos packed her possessions in her pack and fled.  &quot;I am not what I have been, and I will not be what they want.  I am Marlos Battleborne, Bard to the Warlord!&quot; She growled to herself to cover the words that she ached to say, that burned her mind.  &quot;First Bard of Neriak&quot;<br>
